Those three methods (`OnStart`, `OnSleep`, `OnResume`) **still exist** on `Microsoft.Maui.Controls.Application`, so your existing overrides will compile and work.

However, MAUI also introduces **Window lifecycle events**, which are the preferred approach:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnStart   */ };
        window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnResume  */ };
        window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* replaces OnSleep   */ };

        // Additional events not available in Xamarin.Forms:
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => { };
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => { };
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => { };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window Event | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `OnStart()` | `Created` | Fires once on launch |
| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` | App goes to background |
| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` | App returns to foreground |
| — | `Activated` / `Deactivated` | New: window focus changes |
| — | `Destroying` | New: window being destroyed |

The Window-based approach is preferred because it supports **multi-window scenarios** (especially on iPad/desktop) where per-window lifecycle tracking matters.
